No obvious reason was stated.
But online l...";s:7:"blog_id";s:11:"tech-ticker";s:14:"post_timestamp";i:1398452460;s:12:"post_content";s:3563:"<p>Vic Gundotra, the head of Google+, announced his departure from Google today.</p>
<p>No obvious reason was stated.</p>
<p>But online leaks pointed out that this might have been the direct result of Google backing away from the original Google+ plan.</p>
<p>To wrap it up in a nutshell, Google is apparently slowly planning on pulling the Google+ plug: it will no longer be aligned to Facebook and Twitter. It will also not be pushed onto and into every product Google releases. This rumored shift will most probably shake the Google boat: around 1000 employees will hence be moved to other divisions with Google Hangouts and Google+ Photos teams supposedly moved to Android.</p>
<p>Moving away from the rumors, it kind of makes sense for Google to back away from Google+. It simply did not gain any momentum at all. Its actual userbase is far from being called “massive” (it definitely cannot rival Facebook in that respect), and most importantly, the people simply… don’t like it.</p>
<p>It remains unclear if the leaked reports are true. The future of Google+ remains unknown too. But the departure of Gundotra certainly is a pretty powerful hint.</p>
<p>And what comes out of this piece of information is mainly one thing: Google is placing more and more chips on the Android betting case. And that makes sense.</p>
<p><em>Source: <a href="http://feeds.feedblitz.com/~/t/0/0/~techcrunch.com/2014/04/24/google-is-walking-dead/" target="_blank">TechCrunch</a></em></p>
